Yes — if you mean **about USD 10 per short experiment**, not USD 10 for long uninterrupted training. For that use case, a small startup can build a cost-effective multi-vendor pipeline, but the reliable core should be **H100 first, H200 second, B200 opportunistic, B300 only as bonus capacity**. The main reason is market breadth: GPUs.io currently shows **H100: 12 providers / 53 configs**, **H200: 8 / 30**, **B200: 4 / 9**, and **B300: 3 / 12**. GPUs.io also says its coverage is mainly about **published on-demand cloud instances** and that published prices can remain visible even when capacity is temporarily unavailable, so it is useful as a **market-depth proxy**, not as a live spot/preemptible fill-rate monitor. ([GPUs.io][1])

Among the **dstack-supported smaller backends**, the strongest current trio is **Verda, Nebius, and Runpod**. dstack supports VM backends including **Lambda, Nebius, Verda, DigitalOcean, Vultr** and container backends including **Runpod and Vast.ai**. On the vendor side, Verda publicly lists **spot** pricing for all four families at **$0.80 / $1.19 / $1.71 / $2.45** for **H100 / H200 / B200 / B300** and says spot can be evicted at any time without warning; Nebius lists **preemptible** pricing at **$1.25 / $1.45 / $2.90 / $3.40** and gives a **60-second SIGTERM** before shutdown; Runpod offers **spot** with **by-second billing** but only a **5-second warning**. Vast also has interruptible instances on its own platform, but dstack’s `vastai` backend currently says **on-demand only, with spot coming soon**, so I would not treat Vast interruptible as first-class capacity in a strict dstack-only scheduler yet. ([Dstack][2])

**H100** is the only family I would make foundational for “maximum availability” outside the hyperscalers. Public smaller-player supply today spans names like **Thunder Compute, Vast.ai, Runpod, Verda, and DigitalOcean**; Runpod alone lists H100 across **US, Japan, Netherlands, and Norway**, and GPUs.io’s current public floor is **$1.38/GPU-hour**. That is the deepest pool, the widest geography, and the easiest place to absorb spot interruptions without stalling the queue. ([GPUs.io][3])

**H200** is the best memory-heavy compromise. It is materially thinner than H100, but still broad enough to be a real second tier: GPUs.io currently tracks **8 providers / 30 configs**, with dstack-relevant public listings from **Verda, Runpod, and DigitalOcean**, and an overall public floor of **$2.29/GPU-hour**. If your workloads are VRAM-bound, H200 is the most practical fallback that still has multi-vendor depth. ([GPUs.io][4])

**B200** is usable, but thin. GPUs.io currently shows **4 providers / 9 configs**, and the visible public market is concentrated in **Vast.ai, Verda, Runpod, and Beyond.pl**. That is enough to opportunistically schedule short jobs, but not enough that I would build the default queue around it if your goal is “always find something soon.” ([GPUs.io][5])

**B300** is still scarce for self-serve, low-cost, multi-vendor automation. GPUs.io shows **3 providers / 12 configs**; the public floor is currently **Runpod at $6.19/GPU-hour**, Verda lists B300 publicly, but Nebius’s B300 offer is currently in a **private `uk-south1` region not available to new customers**, and some public listings such as **Sesterce** are marked unavailable. DigitalOcean’s reviewed pricing page exposes B300 as a **reserved/contact-sales** product rather than normal self-serve on-demand. In other words: B300 is real, but it is not yet a dependable cheap public spot layer. ([GPUs.io][6])

On a **USD 10 per experiment** budget, the economics are actually pretty good for short runs. At Verda’s published spot rates, **$10 buys about 12.5 H100 GPU-hours, 8.4 H200, 5.8 B200, or 4.1 B300**. At Nebius’s published preemptible rates, it buys **8.0, 6.9, 3.4, and 2.9 GPU-hours** respectively. Even at the current public on-demand floors on GPUs.io, **$10 still buys about 7.2 H100 GPU-hours, 4.4 H200, 3.3 B200, or 1.6 B300**. That is enough for **LoRA/QLoRA fine-tunes, eval sweeps, smoke tests, and pipeline validation**, but not for long, failure-intolerant full-rank training. ([Verda][7])

Because no public source gives a trustworthy global count of **live** spot inventory, my availability estimate has to be heuristic. Using current **provider breadth**, **config breadth**, and whether reviewed **dstack-capable** vendors expose usable public spot/preemptible tiers, I would size practical non-hyperscaler preemptible liquidity roughly as **H100 = 100**, **H200 = 60–70**, **B200 = 25–40**, and **B300 = 10–25**. That is my inference, not a published metric. The B300 number is intentionally discounted because current public supply is narrow and some of the documented Blackwell capacity is region-gated or unavailable. ([GPUs.io][3])

To make this work in practice, I would do five things.

1. **Use three signals, not one dashboard.** Poll `dstack offer --spot-auto --group-by gpu,backend,region --json` every few minutes, keep your own rolling telemetry for **time-to-start**, **no-capacity rate**, **interruption rate**, and **realized cost**, and use GPUs.io only as a slower-moving market-depth sanity check. dstack supports multi-backend scheduling, `spot_policy`, `max_price`, and retries on `no-capacity`, `interruption`, and `error`; if you want this inside your own orchestrator, dstack also exposes a Python client. This is the right answer to your Verda concern: single-vendor monitoring is not enough because neither vendor price pages nor GPUs.io give you the one metric you actually need — recent fill rate on the exact backend/region/GPU tuple. ([Dstack][8])

2. **Make object storage the source of truth.** dstack’s network volumes are only available on **AWS, GCP, and Runpod**, and Runpod’s own docs warn that attaching a single network volume constrains you to that datacenter; using multiple datacenter volumes can improve availability, but the data does **not** sync automatically. dstack can mount a **list of volume names** to one path so each run picks the region-appropriate cache, which is useful, but the durable checkpoint/artifact truth should still live in S3/GCS/R2-style storage. ([Dstack][9])

3. **Design every job to die and resume.** Runpod spot gives only about **5 seconds** of warning, and a stopped Pod can come back without the original GPU; Nebius is friendlier with a **60-second** termination warning. So checkpoint every **2–5 minutes**, save the dataset cursor, seed, adapter weights, optimizer state if needed, and prefer **fresh redeploy + resume** over trying to preserve machine-local state. On Runpod, Pod migration exists, but because storage locality can still constrain failover, I would still architect around stateless resubmission. ([Runpod Documentation][10])

4. **Tier the targets.** For maximum availability under a tight budget, make the default queue **H100 spot/preemptible on Verda + Nebius + Runpod**. If that misses, retry on **H200** when VRAM matters. Keep **Lambda and DigitalOcean** as the on-demand backstop; the reviewed Lambda and DO pages expose self-serve/on-demand pricing rather than a comparable public spot/preemptible surface for these families, and GPUs.io currently shows Lambda’s listed H100/B200 capacity as unavailable. Use **B200 only when it clears your cap**, and treat **B300 as opportunistic**, not part of the SLA. ([Lambda][11])

5. **Warm only the stable layer; burst on the cheap layer.** dstack Fleets let you keep a template with `nodes.min: 0` or maintain a tiny warm pool, and `idle_duration` works on **VM-based** backends but not on **Runpod/Vast.ai**. For this workload I would keep the warm layer on **Nebius / Verda / Lambda / DigitalOcean** and use **Runpod** as burst capacity. If you use Runpod through dstack and are comfortable with it, enabling **Community Cloud** widens the pool. ([Dstack][12])

A simple policy is: probe **H100** first across **Verda + Nebius + Runpod** with a hard price cap; if nothing starts after a small number of retries, probe **H200**; if the experiment is important and still blocked, fall back to **H100 on-demand** on **Lambda or DigitalOcean**; submit **B200/B300** only when the live offer is below your cap and your own recent fill-rate telemetry says that family is actually starting. dstack’s `spot_policy: auto`, `max_price`, retry events, and programmatic API are enough to build that control loop. ([Dstack][13])

So my bottom line is: **yes, this is reasonable for a startup**, but only if you treat **H100 as the default commodity high-end tier**, **H200 as the memory fallback**, and **B200/B300 as opportunistic surplus** rather than guaranteed capacity. The system that works is not “monitor Verda and hope”; it is **multi-vendor telemetry + dstack-based offer scanning + aggressive checkpoint/resume + object-storage-backed artifacts**. If you later move from short single-node experiments into distributed or longer jobs, shift more of the stack toward **VM backends** like Nebius and Verda, because dstack’s container backends are less flexible for that class of workload. ([Dstack][2])

If you want, I can turn this into a concrete **vendor scoring formula + dstack submission policy** for H100/H200/B200/B300 with suggested price caps and retry rules.

